I‚Äôm both proud and impressed with Aubrin Sage‚Äôs determination to get to the very top of this mountain even though it required using a unique lift she had never experienced before and was clearly nervous about.

So much of her confidence and resilience in this moment came from our new and incredibly supportive friends we are visiting (@thefrankofamjam ) who hyped her up but also provided a back-up plan incase someone fell: ‚ÄúCoconut‚Äù was their code word to yell if you fell so the others knew to let go and return to the bottom to try again. It was really inspiring to observe their ‚ÄúNobody reaches the top unless we ALL reach the top‚Äù mentality.  #weridetogether üí™

[Check out the most recent reel on @thefrankofamjam to see a sneak peak at the ride down from here. #ghosttrees]

‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢

T-bars feel like a rite of passage for skiing and snowboarding and are the most difficult lift style to use, especially for snowboarders.

While their implementation at ski resorts has faded in recent memory in favor of the more familiar chair-lift (which is more beginner friendly and easier to use than these surface drag lifts) T-bars are still used around the world to access some of the highest and most advanced terrain because they remain the most cost effective and low maintenance lift option to take people uphill so it‚Äôs great to eventually become familiar with them in order to broaden your terrain access opportunities. 

Anyone else have a T-bar story!?üòÖ

caption:
Snowboarding brought our two families together and for that I am thankful. 

@thefrankofamjam and @alysefranklin are two snowboarders that have spent the last 9 years raising their four girls on the slopes of British Columbia and have been a personal inspiration for myself as we have a seemingly parallel existence.

Every time I see a photo of them all cheerfully riding 6 pack chairlift together my mind is blown at their ability to have spent nearly a decade crushing it on the slopes with kids in tow. 

And then we got to connect and ride with them and two things really stood out to me: their four girls are SERIOUSLY good snowboarders and they‚Äôre also really kind and supportive humans. 

What a joy it was to see Aubrin Sage integrate into that wonderful girl gang and for Torin Cade to be inspired by 4 year old Roux who‚Äôs ripping around independently and for Samantha and I to have the opportunity to ride with two other parents that truly know what we‚Äôve endured the last five years of raising tiny humans on the slopes.

We had one day to ride together and we sure made the most of it with T-bars, ghost trees, beaver tails, side hits, tree runs, double black diamonds and snow sprays a plenty as this crew ROCKED it so hard and did it while laughing and supporting each other. 

Thank you so much Robbie, Alyse, Reid, Rowyn, Collyns and Roux for sharing your time and your home mountain with us.ü´∂

‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢

A good friend of mine sat next to me on a chairlift 10 years ago and said ‚Äúsnowboarding is cool and all but it‚Äôs really about being out here together with your friends‚Äù and I couldn‚Äôt agree more.

There were a lot of highlights to our week spent in British Columbia but none brighter than our time spent becoming friends with a family I‚Äôve admired for years now. #weridetogether #alwaystandingsideways @hellobc

caption:
This is our ‚Äòwhy‚Äô.

Not because we want our children to be incredible snowboarders or Olympic champions. This is simply one of the ways we choose to be active, be outside and be together. 

Sliding on snow is an amazing feeling we all enjoy but it is the in-between moments that we truly love. The chairlift chats and post tumble giggles. The mountain top views and the snowy forest snack times. There are critical life lessons baked into everything we do, snowboarding included, and the last five years of seeing the world through our children‚Äôs eyes have been the best years of our lives and I hope some of our joy and dedication and love shines through in all of our content. 

I felt Inspired to share this reel after @thefrankofamjam just reminded us this was the first video he saw of ours that captured his attention because he and @alysefranklin have lived a seemingly parallel existence, sharing the love of riding sideways with their four girls starting at a very young age (well before we had a tiny Aubrin Sage on a snowboard and before the @mdxone harness even existed!)

This video was also posted 5 days before the ‚ÄòStuckasaurus‚Äô video went live (and globally viral) thus changing our lives forever yet nothing remains more true now than the sentiment I expressed in THIS video on January 28, 2022. üíõ

caption:
Over 10 years of Subaru ownership and the infinite memories made makes this a DREAM partnership with @subaru_usa! ‚ù§Ô∏è 

I remember vividly having two hands tightly pressed to the steering wheel of our 2013 WRX as we cautiously brought home an hours old baby as first time parents. 

My first father-daughter overnight adventure was spent sleeping in the back of our 2003 forester on top of a 7,000 foot tall mountain.

In 2022 we placed all of our trust into our brand new 2022 Outback Wilderness to support an incredibly ambitious two month road trip touring the American West with two young children. A trip that to this day brings me to tears when I think about all we saw and experienced together while discovering a mass on my body. I‚Äôll never forget the long evening driving the family in our Outback through one of the worst snowstorms of my life over a Cascade mountain pass in order to be on time for the long awaited surgery to address my medical issues.

We owe so much of our adventurous lifestyle to Subaru and it was finally time to trade in our beloved WRX for something a little bit bigger and more rugged as we continue exploring the wild places of the Pacific North West and beyond.

Thank you SO much @subaru_usa for supporting and trusting us to share some of our past AND upcoming adventures as we continue our journey in the 2024 Subaru Ascent Onyx!

Any one else have a Subaru love story to share!?

I‚Äôm offering up this behind-the-scenes sufferfest reel for perspective when you see us riding powder. 

Snowboarding powder is like surfing water but with even less friction. Speed is a must to stay a float otherwise‚Ä¶you‚Äôll be swimming. It can be very challenging and after a few situations like this there will always be that lingering thought in the back of your mind that if you go down, THIS is the consequence.

The stakes can be high, especially with tiny kids and this is the dad-ication not often seen in our reels because pulling out the camera is the last thing in my mind during a good sufferfest but if there was any doubt that snowboarding with young kids takes a lot of work, hopefully this squashes it!

caption:

The future looks bright and I‚Äôd like to think we share a glimpse into it right here in our little corner of the internet. 

There‚Äôs also a whole lot more going on than learning how to snowboard. We‚Äôre cultivating important life long traits including confidence, resilience, perseverance and critical thinking that are guaranteed to be valuable to our children‚Äôs future no matter what they choose to do.

caption:
Put a boogie in it.ü§ß

Lately I‚Äôve been jotting down notes that come to mind on a whim or after reading a comment. I‚Äôve got a note document that‚Äôs probably 10 pages long with fragmented thoughts and feelings about anything and everything you could imagine pertaining to parenting and the frequent Olympics comments and the social media culture we‚Äôre immersed in but simultaneously at odds with and just can‚Äôt find the time or energy to articulate anything at depth lately.

Part of the issue is that I don‚Äôt want to come off as if I‚Äôm speaking from a place of authority as I know I‚Äôm not and that‚Äôs not something I‚Äôm interested in pretending to do on here. I do know that people find plenty of little pieces of education or wisdom from our content and I always appreciate hearing about those takeaways but I‚Äôm not here to tell people what they should or shouldn‚Äôt be doing as I think it‚Äôs far more powerful to speak through actions rather than words.

The only thing I can say with certainty is that I‚Äôm going to keep doing what I love and value most which is spending as much time as possible outside with the people I love.

That‚Äôs it. That‚Äôs the end goal. 
There doesn‚Äôt have to be a higher aspiration.

I find great joy in being immersed in each stage of our kids childhood while it‚Äôs happening because I‚Äôm acutely aware it will be a fleeting memory in no time. I know there‚Äôs a whole mess of generational trauma woven throughout society and it‚Äôs our difficult job to break the cycle and instill (and cultivate) attributes of empowerment, resiliency, empathy and confidence so that our children can move forward in whatever direction they choose and have the tools to overcome the inevitable barriers they will face with grit and grace.

Now that I re-read that I guess I do have lofty aspirations but they are not for our kids to be champions (as recognized by society with a gold medal) and instead to be champions of whatever self-motivated pursuit or cause they choose to apply themselves too.

I‚Äôm just showing up for our kids each and every day and trying to be the best person I can be until my ashes fly.

This is my ‚Äòsuccess.‚Äô

caption:
‚ÄúI can do it!‚Äù üí™

‚Ä¶and the way she looked at me and said ‚ÄúI know where I‚Äôm going‚Ä¶üòè‚Äù

I initially planned on dropping this little line on my own and having A.Sage ride the trail around to meet me but I was happy to pivot and let her step up when she insisted she could handle it.

You might be able to tell I was hesitant but I don‚Äôt believe in limiting a child‚Äôs interest in exploring or trying something new, even if it may seem too advanced at first glance. We work so hard to cultivate confidence and resilience and these are the exact moments to fortify those traits. I will not be a barrier and instead will offer support and guidance and encouragement and be alert and ready to pick up the pieces if needed. 

As we spoke I was micro processing all of the potential hazards and things that could happen so I could be prepared for it and put myself in a position to be there immediately if something went wrong only to watch her send it with style!

This small line is a big deal.
I can feel a shift in her riding, a new found confidence, the next level feels near. Not a product of a progression focused mindset and instead a result of her self-driven interest of exploring and love of snowboarding, especially Powder.‚ù§Ô∏è

Well done, baby girl.ü•π
#fatherdaughter

I think it‚Äôs important for our kids to see their parents, their role models like this, playful, excited, and stoked! I‚Äôm thankful to love and enjoy something so much and to be able to share that activity and the excitement it ignites with the next generation.

caption:
You can pack a lot of joy and memories into your time at @mtbachelor and @visitbend!

We (@chasing.sage) just wrapped up our first stop on this seasons continued quest to explore the best family friendly ski & snowboard resorts and it sure was a memorable one!

Samantha and I traveled to Bend, OR for our 1 year wedding anniversary a decade ago and have been coming back almost every year since, now with two kids in tow but this is our first time to Mt Bachelor and this area continues to provide an incredible 4 season stay & play experience for those who love the outdoors! #mtbachelor #visitbend

The friendly faces and amazing terrain (especially all of the ‚Äòsecret paths‚Äô and tree exploration zones) left a lasting memory and we‚Äôll be back for sure, maybe even later this season if we can squeeze it in!

caption:
I just had the best day of the season so far riding with our 6 year old daughter.

As a storm picked up I decided to pick her up a bit early from forest school and head up to the mountain on a rare 1:00 pm till close shred session.

The snow was good, the storm was raging and vibes were unusually giddy. Something seemed to align and we fed off each others energy and stoke. 

She rode with unprecedented confidence, creativity and joy. It was a milestone afternoon I‚Äôll never forget.

After 3 pow runs I asked if she was ready for a lodge break and she declined. After 5 runs I was cold and feeling a bit beat up (I‚Äôm battling some lingering muscle strains) and voiced the option to call it a day. She responded with ‚Äòlet‚Äôs see how we feel after the next one‚Äô which is a very mature way of saying ‚Äòno‚Äô via delay tactic.

On our 7th or 8th ride up the lift I glanced at my phone and it was already 3:45 and it was clear we were going to shut the mountain down.

Every year there‚Äôs a moment or day snowboarding that stands out brighter than all of the rest. Two years ago on a frigid and icy night-ride session I watched her finally commit to the daunting toe edge turn and begin effortlessly linking S-turns. Last year I watched her ride waste deep pow on an unforgettably light April 2nd pow-day and now this midweek afternoon storm riding session will leave a lasting impression on me as well.

I wish days like this could last forever. Yesterday‚Äôs video was from this day as well and I‚Äôll be sharing more video moments soon as I try to share what is tough to articulate with words. ‚ù§Ô∏è
#fatherdaughter #raisingdaughters
